While any diner in town can turn out perfectly passable Greek food, it takes a dedicated Greek restaurant to fully dedicate their efforts to perfecting the pita, and slaying the slouvaki. Meze isn't quite there all the way, but its bright spots shine enough to merit choosing to come here instead of a greasy spoon diner.  Where Meze really excels is in its selection of authentic Greek appetizers, namely the spreads and the flambeed cheese. By far my favorite was the Meze spread, mixing the salty goodness of feta cheese with a flavorful hit of lemon and the most luxurious olive oil to give the entire mix a smooth finish. The Saganaki, flambeed tableside, leaves a delicious taste in your mouth, with the hit of caramelized melted cheese being like heaven on Earth.  The one place where Meze could pick their game up is on the spinach pie. While most are topped high with cheese and spinach, covered in a flaky hot crust, ours came out looking like half the spinach went missing between the kitchen and the table, and the filo crust had taken a steam in the sauna, coming out understuffed and barely crisp.  Sadly when it comes to a Greek restaurants bread and butter, Meze falls short. Their lamb gyro platter, in addition to being a small portion for the price, comes out overcooked, with most pieces of meat crunchy and slightly dry. Combine that with the hard pieces of gristle that come off the meat makes this a sad attempt at what's usually a hard staple to drop the ball on.  Service can be slow at times with wait staff who barely put the effort in to know the menu - when we asked what was in the 3 for all dip, we were given a bland rereading of the menu description itself. Additionally for the prices, the servings are downright paltry.
I had my daughter's bridal shower at Meze. The professionalism of the staff, led by Jennifer and Carmen made my party stress free. The food was delicious and all of our guests enjoyed themselves.

My favorite Greek place in Brooklyn! Huge portions without any compromise in quality. I tried the saganaki and the trio dip platter to start. The saganaki flaming cheese was amazing on some pita or just bread. For the dips, I tried the hummus, cheese, and eggplant, my favorite was the cheese but all of them were delicious and tasted homemade fresh for each plate.  For my main course I had to try the lamb gyro platter and my girlfriend had the Chilean sea bass with some lemon potatoes. The sea bass was good no doubt but I enjoyed my gyro platter more then any gyro I had before. The lamb was flavorful and juicy while the tzatziki sauce was creamy and cooling. All together we had so much food I had to bring some home but the next day, the leftovers tasted just as good.  Excited to come back for some more!

This place is probably one of the best Greek place in the tri-state. It's definitely more flavorful than greek restaurants in Queens! The restaurant is cozy and the staff there are ALL SO friendly! When a waiter saw my boyfriend looking around, even though we weren't his table, he came over right away and asked if we needed anything. We ordered the trio dip platter with hummus, eggplant and the feta dip. My favorite was the feta dip. It was SO good. If you like cheese, you'll enjoy the feta dip. I can honestly eat that and pita bread all day long. We also ordered the Saganaki and greek sausage as apps. you need to get the saganaki!! Its a fun mini fire show to watch as and they squeeze lemon juice on it yummy. Perfect combo with pita bread. For the entree, my bf ordered the lamb gyro. He liked it very much. And said that the lamb was very flavorful and juicy. I had the Chilean sea bass. It was flavorful and the sea bass was melt in your mouth yummy. Their lemon potatoes were also delicious! I cant wait to come back for more
